Ina Lange (née Forstén; 14 December 1846 — 23 October 1930), also known by her noms de plume Daniel Sten and Daniel Stern, was a Finnish writer, music historian, pianist and music instructor.

While living in Stockholm in the 1870s, Forstén is known to have been friends with the Finnish noblewoman and actress Siri von Essen and her Swedish writer husband August Strindberg, in many of whose works she appeared.
In 1876, she married the opera singer Algot Lange.
The couple had three sons, the youngest of whom, Åke Mortimer (b. 1884), later took his father's name, and became known as the explorer and writer Algot Lange.
The Langes' marriage ended in divorce in 1898.
She continued living in Copenhagen until 1913, when she moved to Malmö in Sweden.
Most of her fiction writing took place in the 1880s, with her notable works including Bland ödebygder och skär (1884), Sämre folk (1885), En skaebne (1887), Med kärlek!
